emmett's extruder was one of the first upgrades I added to my Replicator 1, back in the summer of '12. It was an immediate improvement. Thanks emmett!  
It's been in daily use ever since and performed great. In recent weeks, however, I began experiencing sporadic instances of ghost printing. I just couldn't quite figure out what was causing it. So frustrating!  
Then I noticed a teensy crack at the filament feed hole in emmett's lever. I remodeled it slightly to make it beefier there.   
I also added a little more lip to catch the spring at the high side.   
I also increased spring recess size to match the spring I use. It's one of the common ones out of the standard Home Depot spring assortment.   
The now-quite-gimpy extruder made it tricky to print the new arm, so I had to stand there and manually feed filament as it printed. Awkward for real though.  
But... success: 90 minutes after noticing the crack I had the new arm in place and printing like a champ. We live in the future, friends! Our machines are repairing themselves, O happy day.
Follow emmett's instructions.

--- Description ---
This a weighted poker card capper. It is placed on your hole cards during a hand to make sure they are not accidentally folded. The base is designed with the same diameter (39mm) as a standard size poker chip so this will stack perfectly on your chips when not in use.

This design is of a US dollar sign.
If you like this you may want to checkout my collection of card cappers

--- Printing ---
1) Print one each of the parts.
2) I printed the holder (upside down) and base with line support material spaced at 4.5mm.

--- Assembly ---
1) The holder is designed to have 4 nickels placed inside of it as ballast prior to it being snapped into the base.
2) With the nickels inside the holder snap the base over the top of it.
3) Slide the longer end of the dollar sign vertical lines into the base. These ends are chamfered to make them easy to slide into the base. The parts are designed to stay together without glue, but you can add a few drops if you want to guarantee they never come apart.

Enjoy and if you print one please post a picture!

print_settings.Notes:: The 3mm D-shaft part could of course be scaled for use with other D-Shafts and could be combined with other wheels or even gears or pointers or any number of things being made.
print_settings.Infill:: 40 percent or more for wheel 60+ for tire

title: Wheel And Tire for 3mm DShaft. Use for gears or pulleys etc

description.text:
Here we have a complete wheel and tire suitable for table top robots. The system here is for use with 3mm Diameter D-Shaft small geared motors such as those sold by Pololu.

NOTE: THIS PRINT REQUIRES SLICER SETTINGS FOR FINE DETAIL!

ALSO here is a general purpose multi-function adapter to connect a 3mm D-Shaft motor (or other if you scale it) to any number of things like a gear, pully, lever or whatever! To use this you must be able to merge this piece with some other wheel then print the entire assembly.

The wheel shown in green with the 3mm hub is one piece I include and suggest PLA for that print. For the tire, I use NinjaFlex and it prints out a really nice rubber. both of these I use 0.4mm nozzle for fine resolution as the 3mm shaft hole must be fairly accurate.

The D-Shaft is the trick for this print. I have same printer that makes the green wheel shown from a Simplify 3D produced gcode and then I put the model into Cura and the shaft hole is too small. The right size is where it nicely slides in with a little friction but does not require great effort that noticabally splits the gap and then the wheel is wobbly. I believe a 0.4mm nozzle is required and I used PLA. Please see print settings for details.

You may have to make one on your printer and then scale this to be slightly different so the fit on the shaft is a very snug fit and then it is a very handy piece for your designs.

The full wheel and hub is to a scale that works well for my PLA printing. There is always the chance you may have to scale up or down the item(s) for your printer or for materials that shrink and so on. It is likely only a 2-3% scale change in the X and Y axis would be all that was needed one way or the other.

The wheel and tire design to show off a specific need comes from thingiverse thing called 'Small Tire' by Bastien and is thing 626863. Thank you for helping with development of the wheel with the custom 3mm D-Shaft hub shown here and I have posted my Tip! I made it half as thick using Z scaling then combined it to my D-Shaft hub that is key to this post.

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Duplicator 6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.4mm nozzle is best

Infill:

40 percent or more for wheel 60+ for tire

Notes:

A good printer with settings for the finest of resolution is required for this part or the shaft hole may not be close enough. That is the downfall with this simple design but if you get the right settings it works very well.

I use Simplify 3D and I think the trick is to adjust printing speeds for less than 15 second layers. See the image included that shows dark blue or very slow speed is used for the top part of the D-Shaft and it is this that I feel gets the best detail and best fit for the shaft.

I suggest you print just the small hub a few times and test with your motor before doing the full wheel as getting the hub right is key to a nicely rotating wheel.

Basic Slicer Key Settings for PLA wheel and hub:

  • PLA 205C with bed at 60C. No raft so you get smooth outside face.
  • Primary layer height of 0.2mm but less is likely better and thus prints slower.
  • For nice bottom finish I put down 3" Kapton tape sanded with 320 grit
  • No higher than 20mm/sec printing and have first few layers at 30% if you use Simplify 3d)

Printing NinjaFlex is beyond the scope of this help. Work that out so you could print nicely for your printer. It is a very difficult material and can require mods to your extruder and non-typical slicer settings. Sorry but the tire once dialed in is amazing, like rubber but you have to work for it! Do not use a raft for the tire and do the same trick for either glass bed or the Kapton tape sanded with 320 grit paper trick for smoothest side of the tire.

Of course use the same scale factor for wheel and tire if you have to adjust something.

To use the tire with a really nice 'rubber' sort of material I suggest NinjaFlex but be aware that many printers require custom extruder mods to be able to print the very soft NinjaFlex type of materials.

Ways to combine the hub shown here with your own devices driven by a motor:
I use Simplify3D which I realize may be a bit much for folks but that package allows me to import a STL file of wheel or gear or pully of my choice that I have scaled to the size I want into the package. Then import just the 3mm D-Shaft hub part on this page. Now you have to center them and use translations in axis to put the hub attached to the part you are wanting to drive by motor. Simplify 3D allows that to be then printed or output back out as a NEW combined STL file. The wheel with hub STL file in this post was made that way. Assorted other 3D cad tools as long as they can import 2 parts and combine would work so you have to use some sort of CAD tool to use the little 3mm hub.

You may have to scale this a little bit one way or the other depending on your materials and process as I had some shrinkage so this could be just a tiny bit too large OR may be too small depending on your process.

The 3mm D-shaft part could of course be scaled for use with other D-Shafts and could be combined with other wheels or even gears or pointers or any number of things being made.

Prep work

Sand it down so that it fairly smooth using a vairety of your favourite sandpapers

Priming

I would give the whole thing about 2-3 layers of filler primer. allowing it to fully dry between layers and giving it a quick scuff with some sandpaper in between each layer. This whole step is so that it will be super smooth when you go to pain it.

Paint

Paint it in what ever colour floats your boat. but make sure to give it a couple good layers with the first one being a light coat and then progressivley making the coats heavier as you apply them for even and durable results.

Protection (Important step)

After you finish painting it PLEASE CLEAR COAT IT. If you dont clear coat it the paint will wear away and leave the filler primer showing. description.text:
I have hundreds of hobby paint bottles, some over ten years old, that are difficult to mix/shake. A lot of people duct tape or rubber band the bottles to a reciprocating saw and it works great. I wanted a better solution so I made this device that shakes four bottles at a time without the need for rubber bands or tape to hold them in. Works great.

You will need to cut a saw blade to a length of 4 to 5 inches and grind or file the teeth down. There are two holes to bolt the blade in but I found it wasn't necessary. I smeared teh blade with epoxy and drove it into the slot with a hammer til it bottomed out. I've used it about 20 times to date and the blade has not slipped. Video of it in operation here. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5qyl9-yxdKk&feature=youtu.be

WARNING Since this does attach to a power tool use precautions.Safety glasses, point it in a bucket or at the ground. Use common sense. It's designed so the bottles won't come out but sh#t happens.

A tray box for the game Eclipse: A New Dawn for the Galaxy.
The tray is only for ship's parts and dice.
Fits all expansions to the date: Rise of the Ancient, Ship Pack 1, Shadow of the Rift.

DXF, SVG, PDF and PNG.

Version 3

  • Fixed the tray's height, the lid barely closed.

Version 2

  • Fixed the tray's width which was 3mm off.
  • Added a space for dice

Version 1

  • Trays for ship's parts.
  • Inclined divisors for the parts.
  • Piece to stop the parts from falling.
  • Unused space.

Generating Layout

The units are in milimeters. The function just calculates how much space each type of ship's part will occupy.

def func(x):
     return int(round((x*2.1) + (17+3),0))

bin_height = 190-6

parts = {'Ion Cannon': func(6+2+2),
         'Hull': func(6+3),
         'Nuclear Drive': func(4),
         'Electron Computer': func(6+2+2),
         'Nuclear Source': func(6),

         'Plasma Cannon': func(18+4+4),
         'Antimatter Cannon': func(10+2+2),
         'Plasma Missile': func(14+4+4),
         'Improved Hull': func(18+6+6),
         'Fusion Source': func(12+2+2),
         'Tachyon Source': func(8+1),
         'Fusion Drive': func(8),
         'Tachyon Drive': func(8),
         'Positron Computer': func(8+6+6),
         'Gluon Computer': func(8+2),
         'Gauss Shield': func(7+1+2),
         'Phase Shield': func(7+1),

         'Flux Missile': func(9),
         'Sentient Hull': func(8+6),
         'Zero-Point Source': func(5),
         'Conifold Field': func(8),
         'Interceptor Bay': func(6),

         'Soliton Cannon': func(10),
         'Rift Cannon': func(8),
         'Transition Drive': func(9),
         'Absorption Shield': func(9)}

def see(names):
    name = ''
    length = 0
    for i in range(len(names)-1,-1,-1):
        name += names[i]
        name += " (" + str(parts[names[i]]) + ")"
        name += ' + '
        length += parts[names[i]]
    name = name[:-3]
    if (length > bin_height):
        print("\nOverheighted!")
    print(str(length) + ": " + name)

description.text:
This carriage is a full replacement for your stock Tronxy p802e carriage.

It is compatible with the stock extruder motor, hot end, fans and bearings.

I recommend printing the cooling fan mount and cooling fan duct, as it is designed to fit this carriage's offsets. Otherwise you will have to modify your stock cooling fan mounting bracket and your fan will just be cooling your hot end, not your print.

You will need these non-3dprinted parts:

  • 3 m3x35 screws
  • filament guides
  • 26mm length of 4mm ptfe tube

Some filament guides I recommend are:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1711086 or https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1541411

Once this carriage is installed, you will want to check your origin and set it if needed.

description.text:
This is the first Version of the Move mounted Joystick mod. You will need an old or cheap third party Dualshock 4 to desolder the left joystick and use it for the communication to the Playstation later on.

Still working on an easy way to mount the ds4 pcb with the accupack somewhere =/

What you need :

One Move_Joystick_A printed
One Move_Joystick_B printed
One Dualshock 4
One Move Controller
Three M3x6mm Screw
Eight Wires with 0,25mm^2 or less long enough to connect the joystick on the move to you ds4

Optional:
Plug in Connector for the Cable to unplug the Joystick if not needed

Tools:
Screwdriver for the DS4 (PH0) and the type of screws you are using
One soldering iron with at least 60 - 80 W
a little bit solder
double sided tape or velcro

Build Instructions:

!!!! Be careful at the disassembling of the Dualshock to not tear apart one of the connector cables of the Controller!!!!!

Disassemble the Dualshock 4. After you remove the four screws it will be still attached by some snaps. If a snap or even all break at the disassemble don't worry the screws will be enough to hold it together later on^^
A iink for the full disassemble: https://www.ifixit.com/Guide/DualShock+4+Left+Analog+Stick+Replacement/27764

You can also remove the rumble motors to make the ds4 lighter.

Desolder the left Joystick and solder the wires to the marked spots on the PCB.

Optional: You can now build in the connector if you want.

Put the DS4 back together (Just follow the guide in reversed order).

Now solder the other side of the wires to the pins of the joystick and watch out to make sure that the correct wires are soldiered to correct pins. The wires are now an extension of the pcbs to the joystick.

Now insert the Joystick in the two shells with the same direction that it had on the pcb and use the three M3 screws to close the shell.

The last step is to attach the shell to the Move Controller. Use the double sided tape to do that. The organic shape of the move controller was hard to replicate in the cad program so the shell does not fit perfectly. Use more double sided tape in the center of the shell to make it fit perfectly and you are done^^

If you want to add the right joystick to the second move as well mirror the the two halves of the shell and do it all over again^^

Models of functions used to correct lens aberrations made for LBNL's NCEM lab. Shapes were originally generated as zero-thickness surfaces in MATLAB and then thickened for printing and exported using Blender. Models can be tricky to print, but the end result is entirely worth it. Support is recommended for all but the "bowl-shaped" models. I had an easier time printing these on SLA machines than FFF/FDM, but both are possible. Wrote a brief article about the whole process, which can be found here: http://blog.madesolid.com/2014/03/printed-mathematical-function/ Yay Math! Yay Science!

Printing on SLA Machines is fairly easy.  Provide enough support and print large enough and the models should be fine.  
Printing on FFF/FDM can be a bit trickier, but a well-tuned machine using support that is not overly dense on the models that are not bowl shaped (so that it can be removed easily enough) will yield best results.  
Happy Printing!

title: Anycubic Kossel Delta Plus Bed Level Adjusters

description.text:
After a lot of work on all sorts of things getting my bed level, I finally went down the easy road and designed these bed level adjusters. They work with full glass and can be adjusted while the printer is running allowing fine tuning while putting down the first layer. My bed has a diameter of 240 mm but there is some movement in the wheels to allow for adjustment of bed sizes and expansion when the bed heats up.I lost about 18mm on my build height but considered it worth it to make use of the whole bed properly.

They are not designed to replace calibration. Calibrate as normal to get your bed as close as possible then any areas still out can be dialed in with these. Tighten down to around 3mm from the top of the level blocks so everything is tight and holds still. These are designed to give a small amount of adjustment + or - 2mm any more than that you need to re-look at your calibration and frame geometry.

Parts needed.

3 x 12mm long by 8mm diameter springs
3x 15mm long M3 Countersunk Screws (Normal screws will work if you don't plan to use a full-size piece of glass)
3x M3 nuts
3x M3 Nyloc Nuts
3x M3 Washers
Super Glue (To glue M3 nuts into adjusters)
Old screws (M4) from bed holders
M4 square (Already in place) or T Nuts

Assembly

Countersink your heat-bed (If using Full Glass)
Insert countersunk screws and tighten with Nyloc Nut.
Superglue M3 nut to adjuster wheel
Install level blocks so the adjuster wheel position is dead center between towers.
Sit bed on adjusters and turn adjuster wheels to secure bed.
Tighten bed until it is 3mm above the highest part of the level block.
Calibrate printer
Runs test print and adjust the level as needed.

description.text:
2018 February 3d:

Update of this library published in thing ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2781023) on the occasion of the release of KUMAN 7" LCD enclosure (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2781063), mainly better support for screws to fix the pcb and the lid.

Description:

This thing is mainly a refactoring from the very good library OpenSCAD-Arduino-Mounting-Library / arduino.scad from kellyegan ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64008 )
This library uses tbuser's pin library for the pin mounts: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10541

At first I used it to print boxes for arduinos. Then I began to add designs to the library to make boxes for Grove shields. After four or five additions, it began fastidious to add to new designs to the global variables of the main file of the library.

This lead me to do this refactoring.

Custom PCB

Now you can add a new design without modifying the library, just creating a new file for your new design.
Just duplicate one of the original designs, for example 11_ETHERNET.scad as MyCustomPCB.scad.
Then with the search and replace functionnality of a text editor, replace all occurences of "ETHERNET" into "MyCustomPCB".
Then adjust the global variables
MyCustomPCB_BoardShape
MyCustomPCB_Components
MyCustomPCB_Holes
MyCustomPCB_Plots
to the geometry of you PCB.

While making boxes for SeeedStudio Grove shields I've made a very rudimentary tool in FreePascal to facilitate import of the geometry from Eagle files:
https://github.com/jsuzineau/pascal_o_r_mapping/tree/master/electronic/OpenSCAD_from_Eagle_File
This tool is not perfect, the data is not always at the same path in the xml Eagle file.
It's likely you'll have to modify and recompile it in Lazarus ( http://www.lazarus-ide.org/ ) for use with your own Eagle files.
I don't know if this is possible, but the top would be to be have a plugin in Eagle software with a source code generator which can produce this scad file.

Custom Screw housings

I added the capability of adding custom screw housings.
You can decide which corner needs to be screwed using parameter _lid_screws.
For example if you want screw housings on corners 2, 3 and 4, pass the parameter _lid_screws= "234".
If a connector is too close to the screw, you can move a screw towards the outside of the box with the parameter _lid_screws_outer .
For example if you want to move screw housings outside on corners 3 and 4, pass the parameter _lid_screws_outer="34".

Custom Screw Shape

You can customize the shape of the screws by changing Lid_screw.scad.
This file is a kind of alias to a type of screw defined in another file like vis_M3_5_x_16.scad or vis_ronde_M3_5_x_15.scad.
For example you can duplicate vis_ronde_M3_5_x_15.scad to MyScrew.scad, search and replace vis_ronde_M3_5_x_15 to MyScrew in MyScrew.scad and Lid_screw.scad, and adapt MyScrew.scad to the geometry of the screws you have on hand.

Lid_screw_vis_M3_5_x_16.scad is a copy of Lid_screw.scad which points to vis_M3_5_x_16.scad.

Licence

The original library is under MIT Licence so I kept this license for the refactored code.
I usually use GNU LGPL Licence for my work so I kept this license for my personal libraries used in this refactoring that are already published elsewhere.

Notes

08_YUN.scad, 09_INTELGALILEO.scad and 10_TRE.scad are just place-holders, they are not implemented.

My second version of a cooling fan for the Geeetech Rostock 301.
Check my other design for more hints and tips. (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2253022)

I also made an adaptor to mount a 60mm fan. Not because I had too few cooling, but as a test... I want to go 60mm for the hotend itself, in an attempt to improve temperature break and retraction.

  • Prints without support - with "the legs/air pipes" up in the air. Rotate the "upper.stl" for this purpose on your slicer buildplate.
  • 5 or 6 bottom and toplayers
  • Flow 105% - a bit fatter than I'm used to, to ensure "air tightness"

... once more: in several iterations.
I figured that I had to correct the major problem with my first cooling fan, which is a reduced build area due to collisions with the delta-rods.
So this new fan had to go on top of (the already heavy) moving parts of this printer - I needed an octopus alike design! - I don't really recognize the animal though in this eventually functional design :D

  • I also knew that my printer (and/or skills) suck wrt retract (your best settings on this printer always welcome) so I have tried to keep all objects on a layer connected.
  • Since I also didn't want to use support, I've added chamfers (45°) and kept as many angles as possible below 75-65°. Also I put my trust in bridging small areas.
  • The nozzle itself is only 5mm away from the PLA, but not melting the PLA. I believe this is because of the different walls I've connected to the "nozzle cap". These walls disperse the heat into the rest of the design - which is by the way cooling itself, du-uh.
  • You can also notice "cooling grids" in the bottom part, these are both estetical as functional. They open up an enclosed air pocket in the design, avoiding it to overheat (again: I like to believe)

Let's see how this design will keep up in the next months.
A freely moving hotend over the whole print plate is at least already a confirmed achievement!

description.text:
UPDATE!
Introducing the Delidder.Turbo² with twice the turbos you can't go wrong! Delidder.Turbo², with backwards compatible worker/clamping mech that fits Dawnaurs original Delid tool! Twice as many turbos means you can print the body faster and have a simpler solid worker/clamping tool to delid and reassemble your CPU's. Making the job faster and easier than ever.

Thanks to Dawnaur for the CPU Delid tool! 771/775/1150/1151/1155/1156.

VERSION 2
This may be my Delidder's 'final form', but we will have to wait until the next episode to find out! Version 2, brings a much simpler design to the table that should make it easier to print and much easier to use. The new worker/clamp has a top mount universal coin slot 2mm x 32mm. Thanks to Chris(AKA gamertaboo) for being my beta tester and giving me the idea for v2.

VERSION 1
I wanted the ability to clamp down the IHS for reassembly and re-silicone of the IHS back to its rightful protective place over the DIE. So I remixed and created what I like to call the Delidder.Turbo! (Thanks Dilbert) The core mechanism of which is still Dawnaur's reliable build tested many times. (I have had to modify the worker height to fit into my model as well.) All I have done is attempt to add a strong clamp area for the IHS reassembly.

Similar parts to Dawnaur's original
Main worker:
1x M8 Bolt, 40mm +
1x M8 Nut

Clamping/Reassemby:
1x M8 Bolt, 30mm +
1x M8 Nut

A few spare coins, (Finally find a use for my loose change!):
1x Small one for Main Worker body (Universal coin slot 2mm x 32mm)
1x Larger one for in between IHS and the M8 blot during clamping/reassembly.

Keep in mind when clamping the IHS back on that this is a hefty M8 bolt, do not over tighten and damage the DIE. We want to achieve a pressure similar to what the CPU will have locked down in its socket on the motherboard.

CHANGE LOG:
9th Dec 2017:
Released Delidder.Turbo², with a backwards compatible worker/clamping mech that fits Dawnaurs original as well!

8th Dec 2017:
Created second worker model with a 22mm x 2mm coin slot, that will fit 'real' coins such as an American Penny or Dime. :) Added: "Delidder.TurboV1-WorkersSmallerTOPMountCoin22mmMERICAX"

7th Dec 2017:
Remade the Worker model to be slightly smaller height & top mount coin slot so that it can slide in from end and coin can be fitted after. Replaced model with "Delidder.TurboV1-WorkersSmallerTOPMountCoinX.stl"

Testers are needed and feedback is always welcome. Lets learn together! :)

title: Anycubic i3 Mega partfan monstrosity
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Boxy, but good (enough).

  • Includes a part that is effectively a remix of: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2479809
  • Borrows dimensions between fixing bolts from: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2457516
  • This is an attempt to get partfan coverage from both/all sides, while retaining the original plate mount to the bearings. After several attempts I gave up in disgust with the quest to design something elegant, and just settled for monstrous and temporary: I am a little bit over trying to modify the mega's existing hotend, so this is simply a temporary means of getting better part cooling while I print components for an entirely different printer.
  • I may eventually revise this later, but it will likely be in a version that completely replaces the megas hotend compartment right back to the X carriage bearings.
  • It's not pretty, and despite having a COD LED inside it to illuminate the nozzle it's almost impossible to see underneath the ducts anyway, and the LED reaaaaaly needs a trimpot to turn the light down a little. So consider the COB LED slot completely optional. I also soldered the connections to it so they exit towards the leds light emitting surface, so the slots I allowed for wiring to exit may not be big enough for your standard lazily soldered fat blobs of solder and a wire direction change... maybe, maybe not.
  • The top bolt on the partfan doesnt fit, due to an oversight, so mine runs with it missing.
  • LED COB 26x16mm has a heatsink stuck to it's metal side:
  • heatsink 14x14x6mm (7x1mmVanes, typically sold in combination with an even smaller one for use on raspberry pi)
  • The partfan outlets just click in, helps if you put the short end that's closest to the actual partfan in first, and then force the further edge in last.
  • No supports, bridging sucks a bit on the partfan outlets, but it doesn't create enough surface roughness to pull the airflow onto the heatsink, so it's ok. You could try separating them from the other parts, flipping them, use supports, and make the airflow surface nice and smooth by printing it as the top face. But I didn't bother.
  • The partfan is a 5015 blower, some are stronger than others. I picked the strongest I had.
  • The heatsink fan is still the stock 4010

  • None of the nuts require a print-pause, but it is designed for square M3 nuts... which you may not have. Gluing in a hex nut would also work. I use glue to lightly tack several of them in just to make assembly easier.

title: Stepped Raft for Bottom Up Resin Printers

description.text: Detachment of a print from the build plate on bottom up resin printers is a common print failure. The ratio of surface area attached to the build plate to the cross sectional area of the part is the driving factor for this. Using a stepped raft provides more surface area attached to the build plate and because the edges of the raft are gradually thinner there is no warping or curling at the edges of the raft. The result is drastically reduced print failures due to prints detaching from the build plate. There are other techniques that can help with build plate adhesion and you can watch the tutorial video for those here: https://youtu.be/DBmKDi4QXH0

MiSTer - Case Universal v5.2

I remixed the Universal Case for the MiSTer to now support the I/O-Board 5.2 .

The I/O-Board 5.2 now features a second SD-card slot and a protruding SoG switch rendering the older Case Universal 1.2 version obsolete.

The new case has new asymmetric connector points between top and bottom shell. It has new cutouts for SD-card slot, SoG switch and the a wider VGA connector. To cover the side cutouts for the SoG and SOD-card slot there are separate plugs available as covers.

Another feature are the three integrated buttons allowing to press the I/O-boards tactile switches while the case is closed. The buttons are printed in place. Should they not move after the print, try using little force to break them free. I tested the print with 0,18mm layer height and 2 outer shells.

For those not interested in external buttons find a top shell file without buttons:

The original screws of the DE10 Nano can again be used to fix the DE10 Nano inside the case (see pictures). If you find this to be too difficult try using sharp screws to prepare the holes. It works!

title: Anet A8 Z stepper alignment indicator

description.text:
Problem:

On Anet A8 the left and right z steppers get misaligned (skip a step). This can happen because the screws aren't running smoothly or if the printer isn't assembled/aligned perfectly. I've had problems on almost every print with this when I first got this printer. Now that I got things running smoothly this only happens sometimes, usually on long prints, when moving the printer changing the filament etc.

What the thing does:

The indicator shows if the left and right steppers are aligned with each other or not. If they are not you can easily realign them.

If your printer is tuned correctly you almost never need to realign the steppers, if it does you should fix the problem by cleaning, lubricating, aligning z lead screws and rods.

How to use the thing with your Anet A8:

Print 2 rings and 2 bases.

On both z axes, put the ring part on the lead screw and attach the base part with one screw on the printer (as seen on photo). The ring should be tight but still able to turn on the lead screw.

Align left end right carriages with calipers or a ruler and level your bed (as you usually do). When everything is perfectly level, home the z axis, and adjust the dials on both axis so that they are pointing at each other. When turning the ring part on the lead screw, make sure that the steppers are locked.

Now the dials show you the perfect position of your z axes. From now on when one of the steppers misses a step you will see it right away.

To realign:

  • Home the z axis
  • Turn one axis while holding another with your other hand and adjust so that both dials are aligned
  • Home the z axis again

Fits perfectly on my Anet A8 purchased February 2017.

Enjoy!

This version is designed for the micro cameras (19 mm width, like the Foxeer Arrow micro) where you can adjust the FPV camera angle from 0º up to 75º.
Also it has two holes at each side for holding with two plastic ties the GoPro camera mount, the one designed by us, or any other one.
It has another hole at the top back for the vtx antenna.
The only thing you will need for mount this canopy to your Urraca frame, is the two printed parts (this one and the corresponding base for your thickness frame), two screws (M3x16 mm, it does not matter the thickness base) and two M3 autolock nuts.
In this thing you can find two files, is the same design, but just rotated by 210.8º on the Y axis for the top part of the canopy be the first layer in printing. We think this rotated version is slightly stronger and better looking than the one not rotated. Let us know about it.

description.text:
https://youtu.be/xaqa1iWEaAY
We needed a test jig that would slowly and smoothly pull on an electromagnet for a science fair project. So borrowing jsteuben's worm gear (www.thingiverse.com/thing:343922) we assembled this test jig.

Changes to the original worm gear include: Reducing the diameter of the short axle shaft for the horizontal large gear so it will spin more freely. Split the vertical worm gear in half and flipped the upper half upside down so it will print the gear threads cleanly (no clean up after!) and added a 10mm hex shaft to tightly hold the vertical gear together. Created a good crank handle to drive the worm gear. Also added a threaded shaft to the large horizontal gear so we could drive our project sled in and out very slowly.
